The pro-reform coalition has collected 5.2 million signatures, 4.2 million more than it needed to commence the referendum process on the Constitution of Kenya (Amendment) Bill 2020.
Since 2014, the World Bank has ranked East Africa’s economic, financial and transport hub as a lower middle-income country. Despite its growing entrepreneurial middle class, steady growth and robust regional and global leadership, political instability hangs like the Sword of Damocles over its dream of becoming an upper middle income economy by 2030.





Kenya’s power elite have herded the country’s roughly 48.5 million people into exclusive tribal ‘garrison constituencies’ with all the trappings of the Jamaican-style “garrison communities”: a nation impoverished by corruption, ready-for-war armed vigilante groups, blind support for local warlord politicians, exclusive development as part of an intricate client-patron system and cycles of ethnicity-based political turf wars and violence every election year.
Destroyed property
Between 1992 and 2017, the game of ballots and bullets claimed thousands of innocent lives, forcibly displaced hundreds of thousands and destroyed property worth billions.
After the calamitous double-elections on August 8 and October 26, 2017, the writing was on the wall for Kenya’s power elite: They had to reform the political system or end up with a failed nation. Even as Kenya’s transition is tragically trapped in the ‘politics of interregnum’ – where the old is dying and the new has refused to be born – its power elite is split on reforms.



