Convinced they have circled the wagons around their challengers in the 2022 polls, the more populist and Machiavellian wing dismisses political reforms as a waste of energy, time and resources. Emboldened by the support of sections of Nairobi-based diplomatic community and civil society, the populists parody political stability as a luxury that can wait.
For their part, the idealists have drawn the red line in the sand. They insist reforms under the Building Bridges Initiative (BBI) framework are unstoppable. The reformists have the state machinery and numbers in the national and county assemblies on their side. However, the idealists have to convince ‘Wanjiku’ – the wretched of the hamlet – that the repeal the 2010 ‘ceasefire’ Constitution is in her interest.
Intellectually, this calls for sober reflection and rethinking of the ‘democracy-development nexus’ in Kenya’s divided society.
After blissfully going full circle through the motions of all governance systems humanity has ever invented, Kenya has the hard experiential lessons it needs to make its choices. In 1963-1964, it had a short rendezvous with a British-style Westminster model, glazed with ethnic-based federalism. It then entered a long era of mixed government or semi-presidential system in 1969-2010.



