Imperial presidency
This era of imperial presidency combined elements of parliamentary and presidential systems within the wider canvas of shades of authoritarianism, including a multi-party stint (1964-1969), a blistering one-party state (1969-1992), multi-party hiatus (1992-2007) and a mongrel power-sharing system that followed the 2007-2008 post-election mayhem.
The 2010 Constitution ushered in an American-style pure presidential system. But the 2017 electoral impasse exposed the serious “political stability deficit” in this ‘ceasefire document’. It couldn’t guarantee the political stability needed to undergird the effective delivery of Vision 2030, African Union agenda 2063, and the UN Millennium Development Goals.
The ringing message from Trump’s America is that countries across the world are trapped in unfinished transitions from archaic political systems and unable to reconcile between capitalist individualism and the populism of democracy.
Kenya’s reform process has to address the nexus between authoritarianism, democracy and development. The country’s experience over the past 57 years reveals three scenarios.
First, in the 1960s and 1970s, Kenya was part of what British scholar Tim Kelsall calls “authoritarian developers”. Like the Asian Tigers, it harnessed the developmental advantages of authoritarianism for rapid development.



