Democracy
Second, after the 1970s, Kenya experienced authoritarianism without development. As the Kenyan Economist, Bethuel Kinuthia, rightly observes in a 2016 study, in the 1970s Kenya and Malaysia were comparable. But as Malaysia leaped forward and industrialised, Kenya was trapped in “authoritarian stagnation”.
Third, upon returning to a multiparty system in 1992, Kenya experienced a decade of “democracy without development”. The ‘Narc Revolution’ after 2002 ushered in democracy with some development. After 2010, Kenya devolved power and resources to the grassroots. Proposed reforms seek to devolve even more resources and responsibilities to the smallest political unit – the ward.





Despite these successes, the post-2010 constitutional order has failed to tame political instability and support ‘developmental democracy’.
That’s why the Constitution must be re-engineered to foster political stability and broad consensus among the power elite to tame corruption, uphold rule of law and consequently spur long-term socio-economic development. Trump repeatedly attacked mail-in voting, which was used more extensively by Democrats. They say withdrawing the students will undo strides made in higher education. The total number recoveries in the country now stands at 72,596.